long_description:
Since the IDE must load all data loaders into memory immediately and
DataLoader's constructor requires a Class of the DataObject the VM will
normally also load and resolve the DataObject classes (which may never be used
for any other purpose) and sometimes associated classes (such as the DataNode).

In the Ant loader I found that at least you can avoid loading AntProjectNode (a
DataNode) and probably avoid the work of resolving AntProjectDataObject using
code like this:

public SomeDataLoader () {
    super (dataObjectClass ())
}
private static Class dataObjectClass () {
    try {
        return Class.forName (pkg.SomeDataObject false
                              SomeDataLoader.class.getClassLoader ())
    } catch (ClassNotFoundException cnfe) {
        throw new IllegalStateException (cnfe.toString ())
    }
}

But this is clumsy to write. Suggest that DataLoader (and standard subclasses:
MultiFileLoader UniFileLoader) have an additional protected constructor taking
the String name of the DataObject representation class. getRepresentationClass
would then load (but not resolve) this class if and when needed--using the same
classloader as the DataLoader has to load it. So you could just write:

public SomeDataLoader () {
    super (pkg.SomeDataObject)
}

Additionally it might be helpful to define a method in DataLoader:

public String getRepresentationClassName()

which would avoid even loading the class if possible. It might be true that for
most uses of the IDE you could avoid ever calling getRepresentationClass() and
only call getRepresentationClassName() but I am not sure if this would work.

